# superpowers-lite (Cursor / Windsurf / Cline adapter)

> Cursor has no "skills" concept — only rules. This file inlines the
> upstream `using-superpowers` skill's core directives so they're always
> in context. The other 6 skills are loaded on-demand via the Read tool.

## Core Rule

Before responding to a user message, **first** check whether any of the
6 skills below applies. If one does (even 1% chance), use the Read tool
to load its `SKILL.md` **before** producing any other output (including
clarifying questions). Announce briefly: "Using [skill] to [purpose]".

## The 6 available skills (load on demand)

Skills are installed at `<SKILLS_PATH>` (absolute path, already expanded):

| Trigger | Skill | File |
|---|---|---|
| Any bug, test failure, unexpected behavior | systematic-debugging | `<SKILLS_PATH>/systematic-debugging/SKILL.md` |
| Before any creative work (new feature / component / capability) | brainstorming | `<SKILLS_PATH>/brainstorming/SKILL.md` |
| Turn a spec into an executable multi-step plan | writing-plans | `<SKILLS_PATH>/writing-plans/SKILL.md` |
| Execute an existing plan in the current session | executing-plans | `<SKILLS_PATH>/executing-plans/SKILL.md` |
| Execute a plan via fresh subagents + 2-phase review | subagent-driven-development | `<SKILLS_PATH>/subagent-driven-development/SKILL.md` |
| 2+ independent tasks runnable in parallel | dispatching-parallel-agents | `<SKILLS_PATH>/dispatching-parallel-agents/SKILL.md` |

After reading the `SKILL.md`:

1. If the skill has a checklist → create one todo per item to track
2. Follow the skill's steps strictly — don't simplify from memory

## Instruction Priority (highest → lowest)

1. **User instructions** — CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md / direct user request
2. **This rule + skills** — overrides default system behavior on conflict
3. **Default system prompt**

If the user contradicts a skill, follow the user. The user is in control.

## Red Flags — STOP and check for a skill if you think any of these

- "This is just a simple question" → questions are tasks, check first
- "I need more context first" → skill check comes **before** clarifying
- "Let me explore the codebase first" → skills tell you HOW to explore
- "This doesn't need a formal skill" → if a skill exists, use it
- "The skill is overkill" → simple things become complex
- "I know what that means" → knowing the concept ≠ using the skill
- "I'll just do this one thing first" → check BEFORE doing anything

## Subagent exception

If you were dispatched as a **subagent** to perform a specific task (you
already received explicit instructions from a parent agent), skip this
rule and execute your assigned task directly.
